---
description: FileMaker editing standards and cleanup guidance
alwaysApply: true
---

When editing code in this workspace, improve clarity as you go when it can be done safely.

- Prefer consistent ID naming.
- Use `id` for the current record or object's primary key.
- Use a typed foreign key such as `idApp`, `idOrganization`, or `idPage` when the related entity is specific.
- Use `idEntity` only when the relationship is intentionally generic or polymorphic.
- Keep logic visually readable with blank lines between setup, branching, data-shaping, and output blocks.
- When editing existing code, improve spacing and grouping so the flow is easy to scan at a glance.
- Prefer simple, easy-to-scan code over dense or clever code.
- Keep comments only when they explain intent, business rules, constraints, or non-obvious behavior.
- Remove comments that merely restate the code or script step.
- Make sure comments are truthful and current; update or remove any comment that no longer matches the code.
- Add brief comments to code blocks when intent or business rules are not obvious, but do not comment every line.
- When touching an existing area, leave it a little clearer than you found it without doing unrelated rewrites.
- When editing a FileMaker script, always inspect the top doc block and normalize it to the standard fenced header shape when it can be done safely.
- Use this standard section set for script headers:
- `CONCERN:`
- `PARAMETERS:`
- optional `CONTEXT:`
- `RETURNS:`
- optional `NOTES:`
- optional `REVISIONS:`
- Convert legacy labels to the standard where easy, such as `PURPOSE` to `CONCERN`, `PARAMS` or `ACCEPTED PARAMETERS` to `PARAMETERS`, and `HISTORY` to `REVISIONS`.
- Remove stale metadata and boilerplate from script headers when possible, including `AUTHOR`, `CREATED BY`, email lines, generator-version notes, and placeholder instructions; keep only non-obvious operational details by moving them into `NOTES:` when useful.
- Keep `REVISIONS` updated with a short one-line summary for substantive edits only, in `YYYY-MM-DD - why-focused summary` form.
- Avoid long `WORKFLOW` sections in script headers unless explicitly desired; prefer body `SECTION` comments for procedural flow.
